hands_on_practices.solution:
We use the given Roche limit approximation for a fluid-like, spherical satellite:
$$
d \approx C \left(\frac{\rho_{M}}{\rho_{m}}\right)^{1/3},
$$
where $C$ and $\rho_{M}$ are properties of the primary body (the gas giant), and $\rho_{m}$ is the density of the satellite. For two satellites orbiting the same primary, $C$ and $\rho_{M}$ are identical, so the ratio of their Roche limits is determined solely by their densities.

Let $d_{\text{Ferrum}}$ and $d_{\text{Glacies}}$ be the Roche limits for Ferrum and Glacies, with densities $\rho_{\text{iron}}$ and $\rho_{\text{ice}}$, respectively. Then
$$
\frac{d_{\text{Ferrum}}}{d_{\text{Glacies}}}
= \frac{C \left(\frac{\rho_{M}}{\rho_{\text{iron}}}\right)^{1/3}}{C \left(\frac{\rho_{M}}{\rho_{\text{ice}}}\right)^{1/3}}
= \left(\frac{\rho_{M}}{\rho_{\text{iron}}}\right)^{1/3} \left(\frac{\rho_{\text{ice}}}{\rho_{M}}\right)^{1/3}
= \left(\frac{\rho_{\text{ice}}}{\rho_{\text{iron}}}\right)^{1/3}.
$$
Substituting the given densities $\rho_{\text{ice}} = 1000 \text{ kg/m}^{3}$ and $\rho_{\text{iron}} = 8000 \text{ kg/m}^{3}$,
$$
\frac{d_{\text{Ferrum}}}{d_{\text{Glacies}}}
= \left(\frac{1000}{8000}\right)^{1/3}
= \left(\frac{1}{8}\right)^{1/3}
= \frac{1}{2}.
$$
Thus the ratio is a dimensionless value equal to one-half.
